name: Germany
comment:
When being in Berlin, you can ride the usual trains by Deutsche Bahn with a usual metro/tram/bus ticket AS LONG AS you're in the area you paid for ( Zone A+B, A+B+C, etc). So if you don't know another toilet, and you have a ticket, and maybe you have to go somewhere anywhere, check out if a train is going that direction instead of taking the subway/bus/train. There are toilets in all trains. They are gender neutral. 
The trains are often unsafe for People of Colour, especcially Black people because we have racial profiling by the police in germany. Also the staff in the trains might be racist, so take care not to get close to someonewearing a uniform.

name: TransInterQueer e.V.
directions: Kreuzberg district, 1st yard, 1st floor, accessible by elevator, bus M29 stops Pflügerstr. and Reichenberger Str. / Glogauer Str., plus a 12 minute walk from the underground statios Schönleinstr. (tube U7) or Schlesisches Tor (tube U1)
comment: social center for trans, intersex and queer people, allies welcome; sometimes neighbours putaway the ramp necessary for a single step to enter the building

name: Marshall Student Center
street: University of South Florida 4202 E Fowler Ave, MSC 4100 Tampa, FL 33620
comment: First Floor, by Food Court (Gender Neutral/Family Restroom)

name: Bread and Roses Food Cooperative
directions: back of store
comment:
Bread and Roses is a safe space that prohibits sexism, cisheterosexism, racism, classism, ableism, and other forms of discrimination. The restrooms are specifically gender-neutral and you do not have to be a paying customer to use them. I *THINK* that at least one of them is wheelchair-accessible, though I'm not sure if there are unforeseen reasons why this isn't the case, so I didn't put it as such (but please correct if I'm wrong!).
The co-op's hours are usually as follows (with some variation since it's staffed by volunteers):
Weekdays: noon-9pm
Weekends: noon-5pm

name: Diversity Thrift
directions: Straight back in the back by the shoes.
comment: This thrift store is attached to the Gay Community Center of Richmond and it totally gender neutral.

name: Mio'L
comment: Queer space

name: Café Morgenrot
comment: Vegetarian Alternative queer friendly space. with many queer events

name: Sonntags-Club e.V.
street: Greifenhagener Str. 28, Prenzlauer Berg, Berlin, Germany

name: Pho Chi
directions: Walk straight in the main door, turn right at the bamboo curtain.  There is a locking steel door behind which is a very clean and stylish single person unisex bathroom not only equipped with a toilet and urinal, but for some reason there are three chairs in there.  I suspect it doubles as a changing area for staff.
comment: This is one of my top three favorite Vietnamese restaurants, greatly due to its magnificent hours.  It is open until 1am.  It is the only Vietnamese restaurant I've ever been to with a unisex bathroom.  It attracts a very nice crowd.  I've met many nice people there.  Although they do serve alcohol as often as I've been there I've never seen anyone get rowdy.  It seems to be popular with road repair crews and others with late work shifts.  It is also popular with couples.

name: Café Tschüsch
directions: ground floor, in the back, single bathroom
comment: queer friendly, leftist place

name: Club Culture Houze

comment: SexClub

name: Central Washington University
comment: located throughout the campus; see the CWU website's Safe Space section at http://www.cwu.edu/diversity/safe-space-project for a map and more info

name: Cafe Brazil

comment: Place is very chill, they do say hi to you when you come in, so might be good to get coffee or something.

name: Stupid Good Coffee1907-1925

Go up on the escalators or elevators to 2nd floor and follow hallway past a newsstand store to Stupid Good Coffee.  Restroom is to left of entrance to Coffee shop in an alcove.
comment: Two stalls, unisex, locks from the outside, 1 wheelchair accessible stall.

name: Rodeo Mexican Kitchen

comment: I'm not sure if it's handicap accessible as I didn't use it. Probably meant only for paying customers/employees. Houghton is pretty friendly, however, so I doubt anyone would yell or get mad if you used it without buying food.

name: Marble Slab Creamery

directions: Single-toilet restroom off the hall of lower Peace Hall is unisex. The six multi-fixture men’s and women’s restrooms in upper Peace Hall, upper Fellowship Hall, and lower Fellowship Hall are posted as gender welcoming, encouraging people to use whichever  restroom that fits their gender identity and which they are comfortable using.

name: Monkey Monkey Coffee and Tea
directions: One to the left of the counter (accessible) and one straight back, up a few stairs (not accessible).

name: Insomnia Cookies
directions: To the right of the counter

name: Noodles & Company
directions: Next to gendered restrooms behind soda machine

name: Carl's Jr. Mangere

comment: Guess you have to be a paying customer. But the toilets are really close to the entrance/exit - so probably could just use them.

name: City Lane
directions: Halfway down the lane, beside The Courtyard
comment: It looks like it's the toilets specifically for The Courtyard, but they are the toilets for the entire of City Lane

name: Fabians
directions: In the back on the right
comment: No problem just walking in and using. Usually open bar times so late afternoon.

name: Jezebel Spa
comment: LGBTQ friendly and a safe place!

name: Cray Eatery & Drinkery
comment: LGBTQIA Friendly Safe place!

name: King Soopers Marketplace
directions: Front of store, far end by pharmacy.
comment: Two large separate bathrooms, single occupant.

name: Mosaic Cuisine & Cafe
directions: Bathrooms are just inside the South entrance.  Both entrances are double door vestibules so not so handicap friendly.  However when my Lyme Disease was worse I rode my segway into the place and they didn't give me any grief about parking it inside the restaurant.
comment: The restaurant owner, Theirry Jugnet, and I have discussed many social and political issues, so I even though intersex/genderqeer/transgender rights may or may not have been formally discussed, I tend to assume he supports our needs.  What he has told me included harassment he's received from conservative diners who felt it was somehow inappropriate not to have gender designations on the two individual stalls.  He seems quite proud of how he stood his ground.

name: Pagliacci Pizza Call Center
directions: Down the stairs in the parking garage.
comment: It is only for employees who work at the call center/corporate office.

name: The Mr. Roboto Project
comment: This venue is closed unless there is a show or meeting and is not open to the public. The restrooms are separated by "restroom with a urinal" and "two stall restroom".

name: Caffe Nero
directions: Upstairs.
comment: Only one of the bathrooms is unisex but they're all single stall.

name: Twinbrook Baptist Church
comment: This is a rare trans* affirming Baptist church.

name: Somerset House
directions: Ground floor in the middle section of the building, opposite the main ticket desk, 25 metres down the corridor, on the right, opposite the restaurant.
comment: Several gender-neutral toilets :)

name: Prezzo Alton

comment: Restaurant

name: Bethnal Green Working Men's Club
comment: This bar runs supposedly trans-safe events, but there have been at least two incidents of trans* women being thrown out of the women's toilets by the bar staff for being in the "wrong" toilet. This is not a trans-safe place.

name: SW9 Bar
directions: Up the stairs by the entrance door on the left
comment: Safe unsegregated wash area in queer-friendly bar. Five or six stalls have advisory M or W notices, but the stalls are very close together and the notices mostly serve the purpose of stopping cis men from peeing on some of the toilet seats.

name: Sleepless Goat Cafe
directions: at the back
comment:
washrooms labled "with urinal" and "without urinal" 
everyone is really welcoming and open there and your can use either one.

name: the New School University
directions: Between Fifth and Sixth Avenues, on the 13th St. side. Ask guards (there may be 2 there) if you can use the restrooms. They are on the same floor (no need to use the elevator) Make a left then a right, then left. There are 2 gender neutral handicap accessible restrooms. You may need to be a student, but I've had luck entering (you don't have to be a student, just ask)
comment:
Enter through doors all the way to the right of the 3 doors.
Open 24/7.

name: Starbucks Coffee

comment: They stalls are gendered male and female, but it's at the back and only one toilet per room so I would rate it moderately safe, good place to test.

name: Starbucks Hampstead

name: Trader Joe's

name: Europa Cafe

name: Boston Tea Party Café
